Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Uruguay. The Uruguayan authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus.
Travel restrictions
Flights from Montevideo are being reduced on a daily basis. You can see current departures at Carrasco International Airport.
As of Monday 23 March only LATAM will operate flights from Montevideo to São Paulo, Brazil and Santiago de Chile, Chile until 31 March 2020. We do not have confirmation about flights after that date. There is one scheduled flight to Rio de Janeiro, Brazil on Friday 27 March but we do not have confirmation that this flight will operate.
From Brazil, LATAM and British Airways are still flying to the UK.
From Chile, British Airways is still flying to the UK.
This information may change at short notice. You must check flights / connecting flights with your travel agent / insurance before booking.
For updates please see @ukinuruguay and Embajada Británica, Montevideo.
For information on how to return to the UK from Uruguay, see Return to the UK.
To date, the Uruguayan government has introduced a range of mandatory measures to combat the spread of coronavirus. This includes:
partial border closure and mandatory 14-day quarantine for passengers arriving from WHO declared risk or symptomatic countries (China, South Korea, Japan, Singapore, Iran, Spain, Italy, France and Germany) and those who have had contact with a coronavirus infected person.
cruise ships allowed to refuel and take on supplies in Montevideo on a case by case basis
suspending direct flights to and from Europe and the US (from 20 and 18 March respectively)
closing the border with Argentina (including ferry services)
only Uruguayan nationals and legal residents are allowed to enter Uruguay
You will need to check the Travel Advice for any country you will be transiting or visiting after or before Uruguay as there may be other restrictions in place.
Further information is also available from the Uruguayan Ministry of Health (in Spanish). You should comply with any additional screening measures put in place by the authorities.
If you need further information about entry requirements, contact the local immigration authorities or the nearest Uruguayan embassy. You should also check with your airline or travel company for the latest information.
Local measures
suspension of all public shows; closure of public buildings such as museums and libraries along with gambling halls and equestrian events; and the suspension of public and private education centres for at least 14 days (from 14 March)
introduction of maximum pricing for indispensable hygiene products and the removal of taxes from multiple products
all non-essential public officials are required to work remotely
The Government has also recommended all large commercial premises, such as shopping centres, close for an undefined period, with the exception of pharmacies and supermarkets.
The population has been asked to maintain social distancing, including through working remotely, avoiding public transport and large gatherings, and staying at home as much as possible. Police Officers will be urging people to avoid crowds.
Citizens that present symptoms are asked to request home health care and not visit health centres and hospitals. Non-urgent procedures should be rescheduled.
Further information
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website. You can find more information about cases in Uruguay on the TravelHealthPro country page.
